## Overview

Fix two synchronous `res.write()` call sites in `apps/server/src/services/session/session-broadcaster.ts` that ignore Node.js backpressure, causing SSE stream freezes when Relay is enabled.

## Changes

### Fix 1: `subscribeToRelay()` (line 176)

Replace the synchronous `res.write()` inside the relay subscribe callback with an async write queue that handles drain events. The subscribe callback is synchronous, so writes must be queued and flushed asynchronously.

Replace the entire `subscribeToRelay` method with:

```typescript
private subscribeToRelay(res: Response, clientId: string): void {
  const subject = `relay.human.console.${clientId}`;
  let writing = false;
  const queue: string[] = [];

  const flush = async () => {
    if (writing) return;
    writing = true;
    while (queue.length > 0) {
      const data = queue.shift()!;
      try {
        const ok = res.write(data);
        if (!ok) {
          await new Promise<void>((resolve) => res.once('drain', resolve));
        }
      } catch (err) {
        logger.error(`[SessionBroadcaster] Failed to write relay event to client:`, err);
        break;
      }
    }
    writing = false;
  };

  const unsub = this.relay!.subscribe(subject, (envelope) => {
    const eventData = `event: relay_message\ndata: ${JSON.stringify({
      messageId: envelope.id,
      payload: envelope.payload,
      subject: envelope.subject,
    })}\n\n`;
    queue.push(eventData);
    void flush();
  });

  this.relaySubscriptions.set(res, unsub);
}
```

Key design decisions:
- `writing` flag prevents concurrent flush runs
- `queue` array preserves event ordering
- `void flush()` fires and forgets from the synchronous callback
- `break` on error stops processing (client likely disconnected)

### Fix 2: `broadcastUpdate()` (line 322-331)

The method is already `async`. Replace the synchronous `client.write(eventData)` with drain-aware writes.

Replace:
```typescript
for (const client of Array.from(clientSet)) {
  try {
    client.write(eventData);
  } catch (err) {
    // Client may have disconnected, will be cleaned up on 'close' event
    logger.error(
      `[SessionBroadcaster] Failed to write to client for session ${sessionId}:`,
      err
    );
  }
}
```

With:
```typescript
for (const client of Array.from(clientSet)) {
  try {
    const ok = client.write(eventData);
    if (!ok) {
      await new Promise<void>((resolve) => client.once('drain', resolve));
    }
  } catch (err) {
    // Client may have disconnected, will be cleaned up on 'close' event
    logger.error(
      `[SessionBroadcaster] Failed to write to client for session ${sessionId}:`,
      err
    );
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- `subscribeToRelay()` uses an async write queue with drain handling
- `broadcastUpdate()` awaits drain on each client write when `res.write()` returns `false`
- Event ordering is preserved under backpressure
- No synchronous `res.write()` calls remain in session-broadcaster.ts (except the `sync_connected` event in `registerClient`, which is a single small write on connection init)
- TypeScript compiles without errors
- Existing tests pass

## Overview

Add unit tests to verify the backpressure handling in `subscribeToRelay()` and `broadcastUpdate()` works correctly.

Test file: `apps/server/src/services/session/__tests__/session-broadcaster.test.ts` (add to existing file or create if it doesn't exist).

## Test Cases

### Test 1: Relay subscription waits for drain when write returns false

```typescript
describe('relay subscription backpressure', () => {
  it('waits for drain when write returns false', async () => {
    const mockRes = createMockResponse();
    mockRes.write.mockReturnValueOnce(false).mockReturnValue(true);

    // Trigger relay subscription and message
    broadcaster.subscribeToRelay(mockRes, 'test-client');
    relayMock.triggerMessage({ id: '1', payload: { type: 'done', data: {} }, subject: 'test' });

    await vi.waitFor(() => {
      expect(mockRes.once).toHaveBeenCalledWith('drain', expect.any(Function));
    });
  });
```

The mock setup needs:
- A `createMockResponse()` helper that returns an object with `write` (vi.fn()), `once` (vi.fn()), `on` (vi.fn()), `end` (vi.fn()), `setHeader` (vi.fn()), `writeHead` (vi.fn()), and `status` (vi.fn() returning `{ json: vi.fn() }`).
- A relay mock that captures the subscribe callback and exposes a `triggerMessage()` method to invoke it.
- The `subscribeToRelay` method is private, so test it indirectly via `registerClient()` which calls it when relay is set and clientId is provided.

### Test 2: Event order preserved under backpressure

```typescript
  it('preserves event order under backpressure', async () => {
    const mockRes = createMockResponse();
    const writes: string[] = [];
    mockRes.write.mockImplementation((data: string) => {
      writes.push(data);
      return writes.length !== 2; // backpressure on second write
    });

    // Register client with relay
    broadcaster.registerClient('session-1', '/tmp', mockRes, 'test-client');

    // Send 3 messages rapidly
    relayMock.triggerMessage({ id: '1', payload: { type: 'text_delta', data: { text: 'a' } }, subject: 'test' });
    relayMock.triggerMessage({ id: '2', payload: { type: 'text_delta', data: { text: 'b' } }, subject: 'test' });
    relayMock.triggerMessage({ id: '3', payload: { type: 'done', data: {} }, subject: 'test' });

    // Resolve the drain promise
    const drainCallback = mockRes.once.mock.calls.find(c => c[0] === 'drain')?.[1];
    if (drainCallback) drainCallback();

    await vi.waitFor(() => {
      // sync_connected + 3 relay messages = 4 writes total
      const relayWrites = writes.filter(w => w.includes('relay_message'));
      expect(relayWrites).toHaveLength(3);
      expect(relayWrites[0]).toContain('text_delta');
      expect(relayWrites[2]).toContain('done');
    });
  });
});
```

### Test 3: broadcastUpdate drain handling

```typescript
describe('broadcastUpdate backpressure', () => {
  it('waits for drain on sync_update writes', async () => {
    const mockRes = createMockResponse();
    // First write is sync_connected (returns true), subsequent writes return false then true
    mockRes.write
      .mockReturnValueOnce(true)   // sync_connected
      .mockReturnValueOnce(false)  // sync_update triggers backpressure
      .mockReturnValue(true);

    broadcaster.registerClient('session-1', '/tmp', mockRes);

    // Trigger a file change that leads to broadcastUpdate
    // This depends on the test setup having a mock transcriptReader
    // that returns content from readFromOffset

    await vi.waitFor(() => {
      expect(mockRes.once).toHaveBeenCalledWith('drain', expect.any(Function));
    });
  });
});
```

## Setup Requirements

- Mock `RelayCore` with a `subscribe` method that captures callbacks
- Mock `TranscriptReader` with `getTranscriptsDir`, `readFromOffset` methods
- Mock `chokidar.watch` to prevent actual file watching
- Mock `Response` objects with the methods listed above

## Acceptance Criteria

- At least 2 tests verify relay subscription backpressure (drain wait + event ordering)
- At least 1 test verifies broadcastUpdate drain handling
- All tests pass with `pnpm vitest run apps/server/src/services/session/__tests__/session-broadcaster.test.ts`
- No flaky tests (use `vi.waitFor` for async assertions, no arbitrary timeouts)
